You may see a fine and small crack on the left side of the buttstock right where it meets the receiver. That has been there unchanged since the 50s at least according to the owner and possibly longer, but thats when it was noticed. Has not changed in all those years. It is hard to see but the last photo is a clear center shot. The bluing is deep and dark all along the barrel and the receiver. The receiver has just the lightest scratches around the takedown screw. If you look at the internal parts and the magazine tube, there is little bluing wear so this rifle may be almost 95 years old but it was not carried or used much. The bore was just cleaned with a patch and looks awesome with sharp rifling. I imagine that a proper cleaning would reveal a near mint bore. The forearm pump has no cracks or wear and it has one screw though it is press fit tight and has the other screw. Original screws are $14 a pair on Ebay right now. The rifle was disassembled, including the magazine spring and it was thoroughly cleaned and properly lubed so it is ready to go. The inside of the tube gleams and most have a century of crud. title: For Sale:  Winchester Model 63  22LR C-1943 production
postcontent:
Hello, Beautiful Vintage Winchester Model 63 rifle in 22LR. One family owned since new,Built in 1943  this rifle has been pampered and it shows. 95 percent Original lustrous Blued finish intact. Beautiful Wood on this rifle with original finish with one small hairline crack by Tang but not threatening structural integrity. Introduced in 1933, the Model 63 was the first semiauto rifle offered by Winchester chambered for the standard .22 Long Rifle cartridge. It had the square receiver that was a trademark of all early Winchester semiautomatic rifles.
A 10-round, tubular magazine located in the buttstock was loaded by rotating the magazine end cap–located in a cutout in the buttplate–and withdrawing the inner magazine tube until it stopped. Rounds were then inserted nose-first into the magazine through a teardrop-shaped opening in the right side of the buttstock. Pushing the inner tube back into the buttstock compressed a spring-loaded follower, applied pressure to the cartridges, and fed them into the receiver where the bolt picked them up. Another feature common to the earlier Winchester semiauto rifles was that to chamber a round, one pressed on the knurled end of a rod–called the operating sleeve–that extended from the front of the forearm; this retracted the bolt to charge the rifle or extract an unfired cartridge. Pressing in the operating sleeve and rotating it 90 degrees locked the bolt in the open position, Unscrewing a knurled bolt at the rear of the receiver allowed the butt/trigger unit assembly to be separated from the barrel/forearm assembly. This made it easier to clean and allowed the rifle to be taken down into a shorter package for ease of storage.MN Buyer must Have MN state ID and complete form 4473.Out of MN buyer pays $40 shipping to local FFL.
